    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-07T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-07T13:00:00-05:00" n="1316"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1316">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/7–744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stewart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-07T12:00:00-06:00"
                            >July 7, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received 5:54 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>429. The Embassy learned yesterday afternoon that Colonel Lindberg<note n="7"
                        xml:id="d1316fn7">Col. Irving A. Lindberg, Collector General of Customs and
                        High Commissioner in Nicaragua; an American citizen.</note> as President of
                    the Junta de Control de Precios y de Comercio had signed and circulated an order
                    as [<hi rend="italic">to</hi>] the proprietors of all business houses in Managua
                    stating that if any citizen closed the doors of his establishment the Government
                    would appoint an interventor to assume charge of it for the purpose of selling
                    off the stock at cost and he would be denied the right again to engage in
                    business. If a foreigner closed the doors of his place of business he would be
                    subject to expulsion from the country.</p>
                <p>Colonel Lindberg is criticized for his action in this morning’s <hi rend="italic"
                        >La Prensa</hi> not only because constitutional guarantees, notably article
                    60 it is argued, have been infringed but because an alien has intervened in the
                    internal affairs of Nicaragua.</p>
                <p>Colonel Lindberg has informed me that he signed the order at the request of
                    President Somoza.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stewart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
